article.description: Kevin Garnett scored 26 points and  grabbed 11 rebounds and Gary Trent added 17 points off the bench as the Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the Utah Jazz, 116-105,  becoming the fourth team to reach the 40-win plateau.
article.headline: Jazz feeling jobbed after loss to Wolves
article.linkText: Timberwolves wear down Jazz with waves of players
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves looked like one of the deepest teams in the league. Just ask Gary Trent. The Utah Jazz looked like a squad that couldn't buy a favorable call. Just ask Jerry Sloan. Kevin Garnett had 26 points and 11 rebounds, and Trent added 17 points as Minnesota's reserves produced 56 points to lead the Timberwolves to a 116-105 victory over Utah on Saturday night. "We just kept coming with bodies," said Trent, playing for the second time since missing nine games with a strained left hamstring. "The depth was a key. The only negative is there's not enough minutes for everyone." Karl Malone had 25 points and 12 rebounds, and Bryon Russell tied a career high with 25 points for the Jazz. John Stockton, who turns 40 later this month, had 21 points and nine assists, an inspired performance that helped Utah rally late in the first half and again in the fourth quarter. Utah trailed 51-45 at halftime but turned up the defensive intensity, fueling an 8-0 burst midway through the third quarter to take a 63-61 lead on a basket by Malone with 6:15 left. From that point, the teams matched each other shot for shot until Minnesota went ahead 92-84 with 8:38 remaining after a 3-pointer by Anthony Peeler and a three-point play by Garnett. Utah twice came close in the final five minutes. Russell's 3-pointer with 4:47 remaining pulled the Jazz to 100-97, and it was 102-99 after two free throws by Stockton with 4:11 to go, but they couldn't erase the deficit. "We made a couple of mistakes down the stretch," Stockton said. "You can't afford to do that against the good teams." Wally Szczerbiak scored 17 points, and William Avery had 14 and Marc Jackson 10 for Minnesota, which opened a four-game road trip. There were 87 free throws, with the Timberwolves hitting 34 of 43, and Utah making 33 of 44. "That's just how it is when you come into Utah," Trent said. "Malone didn't get 30,000 points by not going to the line." Sloan wasn't happy with calls down the stretch, and the officiating crew was booed while leaving the court. "It was a tough loss," Sloan said. "They are a great team, but I have to question some of the calls coming down the stretch." Like when Trent posted up and put a shoulder into Jarron Collins, sending the Jazz rookie to the floor and then to the bench with his sixth foul. Trent made the ensuing free throws for a 106-99 lead with 2:18 to play. "We were starting to get a little fight in us, and that took the heart out of us," Sloan said. "I have been here 18 years and I usually understand what happens, but that was just ridiculous." Said Collins: "I don't want to comment on officiating, but it's one of those things where officiating shouldn't dictate the end result. You've just got to play through it." Russell suggested the officials cost Utah the game. "I don't even want to waste my money, giving it back to the league," he said. "We gave up 116 points, but they helped give away most of them." From the passion and intensity the Jazz displayed, it was clear they wanted this one. But they dropped to 1-12 against the top five teams in the West, winless in three games against Minnesota. "We don't think about that stuff," Malone said. Utah had won seven of its previous eight, but that loss was a lopsided defeat at Sacramento. A win over the Timberwolves would have sent the message that the Jazz aren't done yet. Instead, it seems they'll make the playoffs, but it's a stretch to imagine Utah going very far. The Jazz are 0-3 against the Kings, 0-3 against San Antonio, 0-2 against the Lakers and 1-1 against Dallas.

Game notes
Minnesota's Flip Saunders coached his 499th NBA game, all with the Timberwolves. ... Jackson was called for a flagrant foul early in the third period after wrapping up Malone with a forearm to the face. ... Sloan got a technical early in the fourth for yelling at referee Marc Davis. ... The Timberwolves, who lost to the Spurs on Friday, are 8-7 on the first night of back-to-back games and 9-6 on the second night. ... The Jazz had won four straight at home, going back to January because of the three-week road trip forced by the Winter Olympics.
